headline: France adopts the Duplomb Law, upholding ban on controversial insecticide
description: President Emmanuel Macron signed into law the modified bill after the Constitutional Council, the country's highest court, struck down the contested provision about the reintroduction of acetamiprid, a bee-killing pesticide.

headline: Taylor Swift announces 12th album 'The Life of a Showgirl' for 'pre pre-order'
description: This is the follow-up to Swift's last studio album, 'The Tortured Poets Department,' which was released last year and sold 1.4 million copies the first day.  A disclaimer on her site notes that the album's release date has not yet been announced, and but that it will ship before October 13.

headline: The remarkable and unforgettable images of painter Ithell Colquhoun, on display in London
description: Tate Britain is dedicating a major retrospective to the British surrealist, who has been unjustly overlooked for far too long. Her work is a revelation.

headline: For young underground partiers, Paris is 'a playground in motion'
description: 'Why Do We Party?' (5/6). In Paris and its outskirts, clandestine parties are held in discreet locations, gathering a generation of techno fans far removed from established clubs.

headline: When partying and protest go hand in hand: 'Celebrating together re-energizes activists'
description: 'Why Do We Party?' (4/6). Collectives and artists are working to put festivities at the heart of their activism. It is a way to fight activist fatigue, attract young people to their causes and escape repression.
